NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tourist arrivals through its two major airports surged 85 percent in the first quarter of 2022 as normalcy returned in the sector after COVID-19 disruption, according to a new economic data released on Tuesday. The east African nation received 225,331 tourists through the Jomo Kenyatta airport in the capital Nairobi and the Moi international airport in the coastal city of Mombasa, up from 121,739 during a similar period in 2021, according to the data from the government statistician Kenya National Bureau of Statistics (KNBS). Most of the tourists, 207,203, according to KNBS, arrived through the Jomo Kenyatta airport while the rest through the Moi airport. The rise in the number of arrivals points to recovery of the sector that was worst affected by the COVID-19 pandemic, as vaccinations in the country and across the globe are intensified. In 2021, the east African nation's international tourist arrivals increased by 53.3 percent to 870,465, up from 567,848 in 2020. Besides the two airports that account for 90 percent of arrivals, some tourists also come by sea and chartered flights.  â– 